      "text": "For the periods ending December 31, 1993, UM&M experienced a notable decline in consolidated net sales largely due to the sale or termination of certain operations. On a comparable basis, excluding these discontinued operations, net sales were relatively stable—with a modest increase in the quarter and a slight decline over six months. Within the apparel textiles segment, the yarn operation benefited from increased unit sales (despite lower selling prices) while the greige fabrics operation faced challenges such as decreased demand and product discontinuations. Overall operating losses narrowed compared to the previous year, driven in part by improved margins in greige fabrics, although these gains were offset by one-time charges in the yarn operation and widening losses in the apparel (retail) and accessories segments. Interest expense increased slightly due to higher average borrowings under the revolving loan agreements. On the liquidity side, persistent operational losses, a stockholders’ equity deficit, and significant indebtedness to its factor (approximately $106.5 million) raise substantial concerns about the company’s ability to continue as a going concern. However, the Company is actively pursuing strategies to reduce its indebtedness through targeted repayment agreements and potential asset sales, which may help stabilize its financial position."
