      "text": "In the first quarter of fiscal 1994, Valspar Corp delivered solid operational performance with a 7.9% sales increase—up $10.8 million from the comparable quarter of 1993—driven by higher volume in the Consumer, Industrial, McWhorter Resin, and Special Groups. Although the Packaging Group experienced a decline due to competitive pricing pressures, overall gross profit margins improved from 25.3% to 26.6% as a result of enhanced productivity, better capacity utilization, and lower raw material costs. Operating expenses rose by 5.2% ($1.48 million) largely due to increased direct selling costs, yet they declined as a percentage of sales (from 20.9% to 20.3%). Lower average borrowings and reduced interest rates contributed to a drop in interest expense, while a $2.47 million write-down of a resin plant was recorded. The combined effects of these factors resulted in a 25.7% increase in net income compared to the prior year. Financially, the company's total debt to capital ratio increased from 5.83% at year-end 1993 to 9.78% at the end of Q1, and working capital (excluding cash and notes payable) grew from $85.86 million to nearly $100 million, reflecting normal seasonal increases. Capital expenditures nearly doubled, driven by the acquisition of a $3 million distribution center in Statesville, North Carolina. Additionally, on February 18, 1994, the wholly-owned resin subsidiary, McWhorter, Inc., completed its acquisition of Cargill's Resin Products Division and restructured its operations, supported by a new $60 million revolving credit facility."
